# VC-Eq-PBCD

This repository provides C++ implementations of VC-Eq-PBCD and VC-PBCD for user-equilibrium traffic assignment. It is intended for reproducibility, algorithm comparison, and further research on large-scale traffic assignment.

## Repository Contents

- `code/`: C++ source files and build/run notes.
- `data/`: benchmark network data for Anaheim, Chicago-Sketch, Birmingham, Philadelphia, and related experiments.
- `paper/`: paper-related materials.
- `result/`: experimental outputs and result files.

The comparison methods or entries under `code/` include `Eq-PBCD`, `iGP`, `iGreedy`, and `iTAPAS`.

## Requirements

- Windows
- VScode
- C++11-compatible compiler
- OpenMP support, for example MinGW-w64 `g++` with `-fopenmp`

The current source files use hard-coded data prefixes under:

```text
F:\VC-Eq-PBCD\data
```

If the project is moved, update the data prefixes in the source files.

## Build

Run these commands from `F:\VC-Eq-PBCD\code`:

```powershell
g++ -o VC-Eq-PBCD -std=c++11 -g .\VC-Eq-PBCD.cpp -fopenmp
g++ -o VC-PBCD -std=c++11 -g .\VC-PBCD.cpp -fopenmp
```

## Run Examples

VC-Eq-PBCD:

```powershell
.\VC-Eq-PBCD.exe 1 4 100 3 8 2 1 2 1 1 1 1 1 > Ana-VC-Eq-PBCD.log
```

VC-PBCD:

```powershell
.\VC-PBCD.exe 1 8  > Ana-VC-PBCD.log
```

See `code\README.md` for the current argument meanings and additional examples.

## Data Source

The raw transportation network data used in this project were obtained from the Transportation Networks repository maintained by Bar-Gera and contributors (`bstabler/TransportationNetworks`).

## Reference

Zhang, K., Liu, Z., Zhang, H., Zhang, Y., Tang, Y. M., & Fu, X. (2026). A graph vertex-coloring-based parallel block coordinate descent method for solving the traffic assignment problem. *Transportation Research Part C: Emerging Technologies*, 183, 105439.

For implementation, usage, or data access questions, contact Kai Zhang at zhang_kai_frank@163.com.
